observations.recommendation:
We recommended, and the Local Chief Executive (LCE) agreed to direct:

The Municipal Accountant to:

prepare the Journal Entry Vouchers (JEV) to record the complete amount to be included in the reclassification to CIP- Building and Other Structures; 

initiate the transfer of completed public infrastructure assets in the Trust Fund to the General Fund duly supporting with subsidiary ledgers;

prepare and maintain property ledger cards and subsidiary ledgers of each PPE account;

The General Service Officer to prepare and maintain property cards for all PPEs of the Municipality and effect regular reconciliation with the ledger cards of the Accounting Office;

The Inventory Committee to prepare and submit the approved Physical Inventory Plan to the Audit Team at least ten calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory- taking activities, conduct and complete the physical inventory in three months or less and ensure full implementation of “One-time cleansing of PPE accounts” as provided for in COA Circular No. 2020-006.

We recommended that the LCE: 

submit an explanation on the use of BGCM for non-allowable expenditures; 

require the personnel concerned to prepare and submit the Report on Fund Utilization, using the format prescribed in LBC 125; and

We recommended, and the management agreed to direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Prepare the Journal Entry Vouchers (JEV) to record the completed PPE in the CIP to its proper PPE account;
Record the transfer of completed PPE in the Trust Fund to the General Fund upon completion and when the assets are ready for use;
Prepare adjusting entries for the misclassifications and erroneous entries made; and
Prepare and maintain property ledger cards and subsidiary ledgers of each PPE account including the CIP for proper monitoring.

We recommended, and the management agreed to direct the GAD Focal Person:
Ensure that all program activities reported in the GAD Accomplishment Report are aligned with the approved GAD Plan and Budget;
Conduct thorough evaluation of the continuing and emerging issues affecting women, including the gender disparities within the Municipality and ensure that costs reflected in the GAD Plan and Budget for projects, programs and activities are accurately determined based on the level of GAD responsiveness of each PPA, as assessed using the Harmonized Gender and Development Guidelines (HGDG) tools in compliance with the minimum GAD appropriation requirement under RA No. 9710;
Ensure that all identified PPAs in the GAD Plan and Budget are fully implemented and that GAD Fund is optimally utilized, amounting to at least 5% of the total municipal budget, through proper planning and timely execution of PPAs as outlined in the GPB; and
Ensure timely submission of GBP and GAD AR to the Audit Team and validate correctness of the posted reports in the FDP Portal, to uphold accuracy, transparency and compliance with national reporting requirements.

We recommended, and the LCE agreed to enjoin the Acting Municipal Treasurer to:

require all collectors to prepare and submit the RAAF incorporating therein the received, issued and cancelled accountable forms with and without face value, and for consolidation in the CRAAF; 

submit all obsolete bank checks accompanied by inventory reports; 

ensure that all collections made are duly acknowledged by issuing the appropriate accountable forms;

impose internal control measures for the immediate remittance of collections;

instruct the collectors to uniformly apply the practice of issuing only one AF No 56 covering both the collections from real property and special education tax;

refrain from allowing the JO worker to be designated as collectors, and ensure that all accountable officers are properly bonded; and

RCCs, the newly designated Liquidating Officer, and the Acting Municipal Treasurer to accurately and properly maintain their respective cashbooks.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to direct the Municipal Treasurer to:

update files in the MTO pertaining to the real property taxes;

prepare the complete Notice of Delinquency in the payment of the Real Property Tax and post the same at the main entrance of the municipal hall and in a publicly accessible and conspicuous place in each barangay of the local government unit concerned; and

We recommended and the LCE agreed to: 

Require the Municipal Accountant to:

submit detailed schedule of the debit adjustments made as the last month of the year;

prepare JEV to correct the misclassification of PPE to another account;

prepare the JEV to correct the erroneous recognition and non-recognition of PPE account;

ensure that depreciation is properly provided for each class of PPE as discussed in PAG3 of the IPSAS 17 and provide for the detailed schedule of depreciation; and

prepare and maintain property ledger cards and subsidiary ledgers of each PPE account.

Require the General Service Officer to prepare and maintain property cards for all PPEs of the Municipality and effect regular reconciliation with the ledger cards of the Accounting Office.

Require the Inventory Committee to complete the physical inventory in three months or less, to prepare and submit the approved RPCPPE to the COA Audit Team and ensure full implementation of “One-time cleansing of PPE accounts” as provided for in COA Circular No. 2020-006.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to require: 

Municipal Planning Development Council to ensure that the budget for the 20% DF is for specific development projects and be consistent with the Municipality’s Comprehensive Development Plan and its Annual Investment Program;

Municipal Budget Officer to incorporate in the SAAOB the changes of projects during the year which includes the specific projects for lump sum appropriations;

Municipal Engineer to observe compliance with the Revised IRR of RA 9184 on the issuance or grant of suspension and extension orders and impose liquidated damages as a result of the invalid suspension/extension orders; and

Municipal Accountant and Municipal Budget Officer to prepare and submit accurate and correct report to oversight agencies for proper monitoring.

We recommended that the LCE: 

submit an explanation on the use of BGCM for non-allowable expenditures; 

require the personnel concerned to prepare and submit the Report on Fund Utilization, using the format prescribed in LBC 125; and

We recommended, and the Local Chief Executive (LCE) agreed to direct:
The Municipal Accountant to:
prepare the Journal Entry Vouchers (JEV) to record the complete amount to be included in the reclassification to CIP- Building and Other Structures;
initiate the transfer of completed public infrastructure assets in the Trust Fund to the General Fund duly supporting with subsidiary ledgers;
prepare and maintain property ledger cards and subsidiary ledgers of each PPE account;
The General Service Officer to prepare and maintain property cards for all PPEs of the Municipality and effect regular reconciliation with the ledger cards of the Accounting Office;
The Inventory Committee to prepare and submit the approved Physical Inventory Plan to the COA Audit Team at least ten calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory- taking activities, conduct and complete the physical inventory in three months or less and ensure full implementation of “One-time cleansing of PPE accounts” as provided for in COA Circular No. 2020-006.

We recommended, and the LCE agreed to enjoin the Acting Municipal Treasurer to:
require all collectors to prepare and submit the RAAF incorporating therein the received, issued and cancelled accountable forms with and without face value, and for consolidation in the CRAAF;
submit all obsolete bank checks accompanied by inventory reports;
ensure that all collections made are duly acknowledged by issuing the appropriate accountable forms;
impose internal control measures for the immediate remittance of collections;
instruct the collectors to uniformly apply the practice of issuing only one AF No 56 covering both the collections from real property and special education tax;
refrain from allowing the JO worker to be designated as collectors, and ensure that all accountable officers are properly bonded; and
RCCs, the newly designated Liquidating Officer, and the Acting Municipal Treasurer to accurately and properly maintain their respective cashbooks.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

require the Local Treasurer and Accountant to maintain property cards and property, plant and equipment ledger cards, and instigate the conduct of physical inventory of agency’s PPE; 

direct all personnel concerned to prepare and maintain the necessary records and reports of Road Networks; 

execute the process of donation on purchased assets given to schools and require the Local Accountant to drop from the books the related cost thereof; and 

direct the Local Accountant to make necessary correcting entries for the proper recognition of depreciation applicable to past and current years.

We recommended and LCE agreed to require:
The Municipal Budget Officer, the Municipal Local Disaster and Risk Reduction and Management Officer, and the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator to ensure that all PPAs chargeable against the 5% LDRRMF must conform with the Appropriation Ordinance; all funds available for use shall be accompanied with well-planned PPAs and embodied in the investment plan; and all PPAs should be backed up with a budget;
The Municipal Budget Officer and the Municipal Accountant to reconcile their respective reports before submitting to the audit team;
The Municipal Accountant to effect the transfer of the Special Trust Fund and to draw the necessary adjusting entries to correct the errors and ensure that the amount and details of the unexpended balance of LDRRMF shall be discussed in the Notes to Financial Statements.
Management accepted the various deficiencies and promised to promptly comply with the audit recommendations.
